So at the beginning of a music copyright case we recognize that the sound recording is what’s important, and at the end of a successful claim, the same.

Why hide the ball from the fact finder in what is often the most crucial stage of a proceeding? Status quo?

Add to that, in calculating damages, often sales are a major contributing factor. Same too the performances of a sound recording. So, it’s a matter of how much money the sound recording generated, not how many copies of sheet music were sold.

This is for composition, sound recording, everything even beyond music in Copyright. 

To prove access, most claimants try to show the songwriter of the defending work has heard the plaintiff’s, or could’ve. Even in cases where a jury doesn’t get to hear the works.
